  <body> <button id="theme-toggle" title="Toggle dark mode"> Dark Mode</button>
    <h4>Confusion / Acute Altered Mental Status</h4>
    <p></p>
    <div class="cns nephrology infectious emergency geriatric General">

      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content">
          <span class="description"><strong>S</strong>: State of Mind / Site of deficit</span>
          <ul>
            <li><b>GLOBAL CONFUSION:</b> Generalized disorientation to time, place, or person.</li>
            <li><b>SPECIFIC DEFICIT:</b>
                <ul>
                    <li><u>Expressive/Receptive Aphasia:</u> Difficulty speaking or understanding (Stroke).</li>
                    <li><u>Memory Loss only:</u> Amnesia.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><b>LEVEL OF CONSCIOUSNESS:</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Alert but confused.</li>
                    <li>Drowsy / Lethargic.</li>
                    <li>Unresponsive / Comatose.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Can you tell me your name? Do you know where you are right now? Do you know what year it is?"</span>
      </div>

      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content">
          <span class="description"><strong>O</strong>: Onset</span>
          <ul>
            <li><b>SUDDEN (Acute - Delirium):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li class="nephrology"><b>Renal Cause:</b> Acute Kidney Injury, Electrolyte imbalance (Na+, Ca++).</li>
                    <li class="trauma"><b>After Head Injury:</b> Concussion, Subdural/Extradural Hemorrhage.</li>
                    <li class="cns"><b>After a Stroke (CVA):</b> Sudden onset vascular event.</li>
                    <li class="cns"><b>After a Seizure:</b> Post-ictal state.</li>
                    <li class="endocrine"><b>Hypoglycemia:</b> Rapid onset in diabetics.</li>
                    <li class="infectious"><b>Sepsis / Malaria.</b></li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><b>GRADUAL (Chronic - Dementia):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li class="nephrology"><b>Chronic Renal Failure:</b> Uremic encephalopathy (rule out acute on chronic).</li>
                    <li class="cns"><b>Dementia:</b> Alzheimer's, Vascular, Lewy Body (months to years).</li>
                    <li class="oncology"><b>Brain Tumor:</b> Gradual mass effect.</li>
                    <li class="trauma"><b>Chronic Subdural Hematoma:</b> (Weeks after minor head injury in elderly).</li>
                    <li class="psych"><b>Depression:</b> "Pseudodementia".</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"When did the confusion start? Did it happen suddenly in a few hours, or have you noticed a slow decline over months?"</span>
      </div>

      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content">
          <span class="description"><strong>D</strong>: Duration</span>
           <ul>
            <li>Hours/Days (Suggests Delirium).</li>
            <li>Months/Years (Suggests Dementia).</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"How long has the confusion been present?"</span>
      </div>

      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content">
          <span class="description"><strong>A/R</strong>: Aggravating &amp; Relieving Factors</span>
          <ul>
            <li><b>AGGRAVATED BY (Triggers/Precipitants):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Medications (PINCH ME):</b>
                        <ul>
                            <li><u>Opioids</u> (Morphine, Tramadol).</li>
                            <li><u>Anti-histamines</u> (sedating types).</li>
                            <li><u>Sleep aids</u> (Benzodiazepines, Z-drugs).</li>
                            <li>Steroids, Anticholinergics.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><b>Substances:</b> Alcohol intoxication or <b>Withdrawal</b>.</li>
                    <li><b>Environment:</b> Change of scenery (hospitalization), sleep deprivation.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><b>RELIEVED BY:</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Familiar faces/environment.</li>
                    <li>Reorientation cues (clocks, calendars).</li>
                    <li>Correction of underlying cause (e.g., fluids, oxygen).</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Did they start any new medicines recently, like sleeping pills or strong painkillers? Does anything seem to make them more lucid?"</span>
      </div>

      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content">
          <span class="description"><strong>C</strong>: Character / Type of Confusion</span>
          <ul>
            <li><b>HYPERACTIVE (Agitated):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Restless, aggressive, pulling at lines, wandering.</li>
                    <li><u>Delirious:</u> Hallucinations (visual/auditory), paranoia.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
             <li><b>HYPOACTIVE (Drowsy):</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>Withdrawn, sleepy, sluggish response, reduced motor activity. (Often missed).</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
             <li><b>COGNITIVE DEFICIT:</b>
                <ul>
                    <li><u>Memory Loss:</u> Short term vs. Long term.</li>
                    <li><u>Disoriented:</u> To Time, Place, or Person.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"How are they behaving? Are they agitated and restless, or are they unusually drowsy and quiet? Are they seeing things that aren't there?"</span>
      </div>

      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content">
          <span class="description"><strong>R</strong>: Recent History / Radiation (Context)</span>
          <ul>
            <li><b>Recent Head Trauma:</b> Even minor falls in elderly (Subdural).</li>
            <li><b>Recent Travel:</b> <span class="infectious">Malaria risk areas.</span></li>
            <li><b>Recent Surgery/Hospitalization.</b></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Have they had a fall or hit their head recently? Have they traveled anywhere recently?"</span>
      </div>

      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content">
          <span class="description"><strong>A</strong>: Associated Symptoms (Systemic Search)</span>
          <ul>
            <li><b>CNS (Neurological):</b>
                 <ul>
                    <li class="cns"><u>Seizures / Fits:</u> Post-ictal confusion.</li>
                    <li class="cns"><u>Memory Loss:</u> Progressive or acute.</li>
                    <li class="cns"><u>Focal weakness/Speech slurring:</u> Stroke.</li>
                    <li class="cns"><u>Headache/Neck Stiffness:</u> Meningitis.</li>
                 </ul>
            </li>
            <li><b>URINARY (UTI - Commonest cause in elderly):</b>
                 <ul>
                    <li class="infectious">Fever (or hypothermia).</li>
                    <li class="nephrology">Decreased urine output (Renal failure/Dehydration).</li>
                    <li class="urology">Dysuria, urgency, foul-smelling urine.</li>
                 </ul>
            </li>
            <li><b>RESPIRATORY (Hypoxia/Infection):</b>
                 <ul>
                    <li class="respiratory">Shortness of Breath (SOB).</li>
                    <li class="infectious">Cough, Sputum, Fever (Pneumonia).</li>
                 </ul>
            </li>
            <li><b>CVS (Cardiovascular):</b>
                 <ul>
                    <li class="cardiac">Swelling of legs (Heart Failure).</li>
                    <li class="cardiac">SOB / Orthopnea.</li>
                    <li class="cardiac">Palpitations (Arrhythmia -> clots -> stroke).</li>
                 </ul>
            </li>
             <li><b>GASTROINTESTINAL:</b>
                 <ul>
                    <li class="git"><b>Constipation:</b> (Major precipitant of delirium in elderly).</li>
                    <li class="git">Nausea / Vomiting.</li>
                    <li class="git">Jaundice / Flapping Tremor (Hepatic Encephalopathy).</li>
                 </ul>
            </li>
            <li><b>INFECTIOUS / SYSTEMIC:</b>
                 <ul>
                    <li class="infectious"><b>Malaria:</b> Cerebral malaria (fever, chills, travel).</li>
                    <li class="endocrine"><b>Hypoglycemia:</b> Sweating, tremor, hunger.</li>
                 </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"We need to check everything. Have they had a fever or cough? Have they been constipated? Have they been passing urine normally?"</span>
      </div>

      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content">
          <span class="description"><strong>P</strong>: Progression</span>
          <ul>
            <li><b>Worsening:</b> Rapid decline suggests acute delirium or rapidly expanding lesion (bleed/tumor).</li>
            <li><b>Stable:</b> Suggests established dementia.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Has the confusion been getting worse day by day?"</span>
      </div>

      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content">
          <span class="description"><strong>P</strong>: Pattern</span>
          <ul>
            <li><b>INTERMITTENT / FLUCTUATING:</b>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="geriatric">Classic for <b>Delirium</b>.</span> Lucid intervals followed by confusion.</li>
                    <li>"Sundowning" (Worse at night).</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><b>CONSTANT:</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>More typical of advanced Dementia or severe structural brain damage.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Does the confusion come and go? Are they better in the morning and worse at night?"</span>
      </div>

      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content">
          <span class="description"><strong>E</strong>: Effect on life</span>
          <ul>
            <li><b>Safety Risks:</b> Wandering, leaving gas/stove on, falls risk.</li>
            <li><b>Self Care:</b> Inability to wash, dress, or eat.</li>
            <li><b>Carer Strain:</b> Impact on family members.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Is it safe for them to be alone? Can they still dress and feed themselves?"</span>
      </div>

      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content">
          <span class="description"><strong>R</strong>: Red Flags (Life-Threatening Causes)</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="cns emergency"><b>FAST:</b> Face drooping, Arm weakness, Speech difficulty (Stroke).</li>
            <li class="infectious emergency"><b>MENINGITIS:</b> Rash (non-blanching), Fever, Headache, Neck stiffness, Photophobia.</li>
            <li class="infectious emergency"><b>ENCEPHALITIS:</b> Fever + Altered behavior/Personality change + Seizures.</li>
            <li class="cns emergency"><b>FITS (Seizures):</b> Active fitting or post-ictal state.</li>
            <li class="endocrine emergency"><b>HYPOGLYCEMIA:</b> Low blood sugar (Check immediately).</li>
            <li class="trauma emergency"><b>HEAD INJURY:</b> Risk of intracranial bleed.</li>
            <li class="respiratory emergency"><b>HYPOXIA:</b> Low oxygen saturation.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"I need to make sure we aren't missing a medical emergency. Do they have a stiff neck or a rash? Have they had any seizures?"</span>
      </div>

      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content">
          <span class="description"><strong>S</strong>: Severity / Screening Tools</span>
          <ul>
            <li><b>AMTS</b> (Abbreviated Mental Test Score).</li>
            <li><b>4AT</b> (Rapid clinical test for Delirium).</li>
            <li><b>CAM</b> (Confusion Assessment Method - Diagnostic for Delirium).</li>
            <li><b>GCS</b> (Glasgow Coma Scale - for consciousness level).</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"We will do a quick memory test to see how severe the confusion is."</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <p><br>
    </p>
    <hr>
    <h2><strong>1. AMTS &mdash; Abbreviated Mental Test Score</strong></h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Quick screen for cognitive impairment
          (often in elderly or acute settings).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Questions:</strong> 10 items &mdash; e.g., age, date of
          birth, current year, time, address recall, recognition of people,
          historical dates, etc.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Scoring:</strong> 1 point per correct answer &rarr; <strong>&lt;8/10
            suggests cognitive impairment</strong> (needs further assessment).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Strengths:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>Very quick (2&ndash;3 min)</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Widely used in A&amp;E, acute medicine</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Limitations:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>Doesn&rsquo;t differentiate acute delirium from chronic dementia.</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Cultural bias possible in some questions.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <hr>
    <h2><strong>2. 4AT &mdash; 4 A&rsquo;s Test</strong></h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Rapid delirium screen (designed for acute
          hospitals, especially elderly patients).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Domains:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p><strong>Alertness</strong> (normal, abnormal, drowsy)</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p><strong>AMT4</strong> &mdash; 4-item orientation (age, date of
              birth, place, year)</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p><strong>Attention</strong> &mdash; e.g., months of the year
              backwards</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p><strong>Acute change or fluctuating course</strong></p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Scoring:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>0 = unlikely delirium/cognitive impairment</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>1&ndash;3 = possible cognitive impairment</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>&ge;4 = possible delirium (needs clinical confirmation)</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Strengths:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>Takes <strong>&lt;2 minutes</strong></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Picks up both delirium and dementia risk</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>No need for patient cooperation if unresponsive (alertness scored
              visually)</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Limitations:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>Still a screen &mdash; not diagnostic</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Needs good collateral history for &ldquo;acute change&rdquo;</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <hr>
    <h2><strong>3. CAM &mdash; Confusion Assessment Method</strong></h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Gold-standard <em>bedside diagnostic</em>
          algorithm for <strong>delirium</strong>.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Criteria:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>Acute onset &amp; fluctuating course <strong>AND</strong></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Inattention <strong>AND</strong></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Either disorganised thinking <strong>OR</strong> altered level
              of consciousness</p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Scoring:</strong> Positive CAM = delirium likely; needs
          urgent management.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Strengths:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>Well validated, diagnostic rather than screening</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Can be used repeatedly to track changes</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Limitations:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>Takes longer (5&ndash;10 min) than 4AT</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Requires some training to use correctly</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <hr>
    <h3><strong>Summary Table</strong></h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Tool</th>
          <th>Time</th>
          <th>Focus</th>
          <th>Best For</th>
          <th>Cut-off</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>AMTS</td>
          <td>2&ndash;3m</td>
          <td>Cognitive impairment (any cause)</td>
          <td>Quick screen in ED/ward</td>
          <td>&lt;8/10</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>4AT</td>
          <td>&lt;2m</td>
          <td>Delirium &amp; dementia risk</td>
          <td>Acute hospital settings</td>
          <td>&ge;4 delirium likely</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>CAM</td>
          <td>5&ndash;10m</td>
          <td>Diagnostic delirium</td>
          <td>Confirming delirium after screen</td>
          <td>N/A</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <hr>
    <p>If you like, I can make you a <strong>PLAB 2 exam-friendly memory aid</strong>
      so you can recall AMTS, 4AT, and CAM differences instantly in a roleplay.
      That way you&rsquo;ll know which to mention in which scenario.</p>
    <p></p>
